%[text] # Create Data Center Models
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_00e5] In this workflow, you learn how to create data center custom library based on your application needs. There are three model fidilities that you can construct - electrical, thermal, and electrothermal. You specify the number of server rack units you required in the data center application and the expected data center power rating.
%[text] ![](text:image:59fb)
%[text] A typical data center has multiple power distribution units (PDU) or server racks, as shown in the picture above. Each PDU consists of multiple CPU servers. The server load or utilization can change depending on requirements. In this project, you can use a custom `Datacenter Server Unit` library to create larger data centers of desired rating. The custom `Datacenter Server Unit` library is based on server name plate parameterization and you can specify multiple CPUs in the block. The thermal model for the `Datacenter Server Unit` library is lumped. 
%[text] Using the utility `createDataCenterWithEnclosure`, you can create a large inter-connected server rack system along with it's thermal model. Run the help command to learn more about the utility.
help createDataCenterWithEnclosure; %[output:42181f6d]
%[text] You can specify the CPU utilization of each `Datacenter Server Unit` custom library as different from one another. To learn more about the options available with the utilities, see [Documentation: Data Center Utilities](file:../../Components/Datacenter/documentation/DocumentationDataCenterUtilities.html). Optionally, you can build an enclosure around the data center or a room to host all data center server racks. The room as specified has a rectangular cross-section. You can specify different wall or glass-window properties and change room orientation to align in any cardinal direction. 
%[text] ## Create Data Center Custom Library
%[text] ### Specify Server Data
%[text] Use the command below to change the server specification. The utility `getDataCenterNamePlateRatingTable` provides two tables as output with some default values. You can edit any of the default values using name-plate-parameters for the utility or by manually editing the table values.
serverData = getDataCenterNamePlateRatingTable(Display=true); %[output:20d67080]
%[text] ### Data Center for HVAC
%[text] Specify a path to save the model library files generated using the utilities.
savePath = fullfile(currentProject().RootFolder,"Workflow","CreatePlantModels","CreateDataCenterModel");
%[text] To create a 20kW rating data center model library with thermal nodes for HVAC applications, run the section of code below. Use the name-value-pair `SaveAtFullPath` to specify location to save the library file.
DatacenterModelName = "MyDatacenterModel_HVAC";
% You must use 'SaveModelAs' and 'SaveAtFullPath' options below to
% automatically save the model.
createDataCenterWithEnclosure(NumPDUunitsX=3,NumPDUunitsY=4,... %[output:group:46e5d85e] %[output:240976e7]
                              ModelName=DatacenterModelName,... %[output:240976e7]
                              ModelOption="Thermal",... %[output:240976e7]
                              RatingDatacenter=simscape.Value(20,"kW"),... %[output:240976e7]
                              ServerNamePlateRating=serverData.nameplateRating,... %[output:240976e7]
                              ServerPowerSystemSpec=serverData.powerSystemSpecs,... %[output:240976e7]
                              ThermalRes=simscape.Value(0.01,"K/W"),... %[output:240976e7]
                              EnclosureName="Room",... %[output:240976e7]
                              PercentAirVolInRoom=8,... %[output:240976e7]
                              RoomLength=simscape.Value(12,"m"),... %[output:240976e7]
                              RoomWidth=simscape.Value(8,"m"),... %[output:240976e7]
                              RoomHeight=simscape.Value(3,"m"),... %[output:240976e7]
                              RoomRotate=simscape.Value(25,"deg"),... %[output:240976e7]
                              WallThickness=simscape.Value(0.05,"m"),... %[output:240976e7]
                              Diagnostics=true); %[output:group:46e5d85e] %[output:240976e7]
%[text] ### Data Center for Grids
%[text] To create a 20kW rating data center model library with 3-phase electrical nodes for power system applications, run this code.
DatacenterModelName = "MyDatacenterModel_GRIDS";
% You must use 'SaveModelAs' and 'SaveAtFullPath' options below to
% automatically save the model.
createDataCenterWithEnclosure(NumPDUunitsX=3,NumPDUunitsY=4,... %[output:group:1ef88e68] %[output:96429feb]
                              ModelName=DatacenterModelName,... %[output:96429feb]
                              ModelOption="Electrical",... %[output:96429feb]
                              RatingDatacenter=simscape.Value(20,"kW"),... %[output:96429feb]
                              ServerNamePlateRating=serverData.nameplateRating,... %[output:96429feb]
                              ServerPowerSystemSpec=serverData.powerSystemSpecs,... %[output:96429feb]
                              Diagnostics=true); %[output:group:1ef88e68] %[output:96429feb]
%[text] ### Data Center for Grids & HVAC
%[text] To create a 20kW rating data center model library with thermal as well as 3-phase electrical nodes, run this code.
DatacenterModelName = "MyDatacenterModel_GRIDS_HVAC";
% You must use 'SaveModelAs' and 'SaveAtFullPath' options below to
% automatically save the model.
createDataCenterWithEnclosure(NumPDUunitsX=3,NumPDUunitsY=4,... %[output:group:89393eed] %[output:6787c392]
                              ModelName=DatacenterModelName,... %[output:6787c392]
                              ModelOption="Electrothermal",... %[output:6787c392]
                              RatingDatacenter=simscape.Value(20,"kW"),... %[output:6787c392]
                              ServerNamePlateRating=serverData.nameplateRating,... %[output:6787c392]
                              ServerPowerSystemSpec=serverData.powerSystemSpecs,... %[output:6787c392]
                              ThermalRes=simscape.Value(0.01,"K/W"),... %[output:6787c392]
                              EnclosureName="Room",... %[output:6787c392]
                              PercentAirVolInRoom=8,... %[output:6787c392]
                              RoomLength=simscape.Value(12,"m"),... %[output:6787c392]
                              RoomWidth=simscape.Value(8,"m"),... %[output:6787c392]
                              RoomHeight=simscape.Value(3,"m"),... %[output:6787c392]
                              RoomRotate=simscape.Value(25,"deg"),... %[output:6787c392]
                              WallThickness=simscape.Value(0.05,"m"),... %[output:6787c392]
                              Diagnostics=true); %[output:group:89393eed] %[output:6787c392]
%[text] ## How to Use Custom Library
%[text] The custom library is saved at the folder location that you specified. You can copy the custom library that was created and build your system model for the engineering problem that you wish to solve. Additionally, use the **Utilization Converter** block to convert a 2D matrix of server utilization data (based on `NumPDUunitsX` and `NumPDUunitsY` values required by `createDataCenterWithEnclosure`) into the vector form required by the large data center created above.

